711055f-b.text:
(1)
West 10th Street (formerly Amos Street), north side, from Washington to West Streets, showing the old Empire Brewery (1878) and the clearing left on the corner by demolition of old 666-72 Washington Street, to make room for the new New York Central railroad viaduct.
In the background may be seen Pier 48, North River.
June 15, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, seen from the roof of the Federal Building on the south side of Christopher Street, and showing the demolition of the
Washington Street wing of the Brewery.
July 25, 1930.
P. L. Sperr.

711036f-a.text:
Empire Brewery, 287 West 10th Street (formerly Amos Street), north side, between Washington and West Streets, built in 1878 by Beadleston and Woerz, the proprietors. The building extends through the block to Charles Street, and used to have a wing at 674-6 Washington Street, which was demolished in 1930.
May 20, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

719975f-b.text:
(1)
Gansevoort Market Stand, northern part, from Washington Street to Tenth Avenue, view north. This view shows the loft buildings on the west side of Washington Street, from Little West 12th to 13th Streets, which will have to be demolished in 1931.
April 3, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, from the ground, two and a half years later, after demolition of 41-49 Little West 12th Street at the N.W. corner of Washington Street.
December 3, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.
(3)
The same as No. 1, and showing a further view northward on Eleventh Ave.
April 3, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.
